attachments.title: Drones to LIDAR, the Freshwater Trust Protects America’s Waterways with Surgical Precision
attachments.text: The river-stewarding organization is one of Oregon’s most important environmental nonprofits.
attachments.fallback: Portland Monthly: Drones to LIDAR, the Freshwater Trust Protects America’s Waterways with Surgical Precision

text: <@U5WML0UBW> is preparing a research report on their broader efforts that we'll get access to later in the week, but for now *here's what you need to know*: The Freshwater Trust is one of the most advanced waterway reclamation organizations in the country. They work together with individual landowners, municipal governments, and corporations to mitigate their impact on critical habitats. We'll be working with them to solve a key challenge: expand the base of people that give them money at the lowest levels. We'll do this by helping show off their technological prestige, and how they're implementing their various models and data-based solutions as well as helping them receive recognition for helping solve this key issue, in the conservation / broad "water" world.

:rotating_light: SPECIAL OPPORTUNITY :rotating_light: there's a completely optional, non-essential chance to take a quick-and-dirty trip to see a crucial part of their work on *stream restoration* on Thursday morning on the Sandy River. timing would be like 8-11am. Holler at me if this is something you're free for and would like to take part in and hopefully we'll have have some availability to take a look at what they're up to and report back.
goodness I want to, but thursday is not going to work for me

LASTLY: for those of you who haven't been in a Summit before, *feel free to ask any procedural questions here at any time*. Summits are a chance to show the broader studio process in a compressed timeline. What we come up with isn't make-or-break, written in stone stuff; it's mostly meant to convey our energy and heart to our clients. In this case, with a pro-bono Summit, we're offering TFT a chance to take part in something they might never have otherwise had a chance to do, so they'll be very grateful to have access to our expertise!

I heard about some of the recent work from a director of the Sandy River Basin Watershed Council at the PNCA environmental hackathon a couple weeks ago. It's so nice to hear some good news about the environment, I'm excited to check it out
